{"cursor":"19445","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nA 'gravitational lens' refers to a distribution of matter (such as a cluster of\ngalaxies) between a distant source (a background galaxy) and an observer, that\nis capable of bending (lensing) the light from the source, as it travels towards\nthe observer. This effect is known as gravitational lensing and is one of the\npredictions of Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity.\n\nAlthough Orest Chwolson is credited as being the first to discuss the effect in\nprint in 1924, the effect is more commonly associated with Einstein, who\npublished a more famous article on the subject in 1936.\n\nFritz Zwicky posited in 1937 that the effect could allow galaxy clusters to act\nas gravitational lenses. It was not until 1979 that this effect was confirmed by\nobservation of the so-called \"Twin QSO\" SBS 0957+561.\n","linknr":392,"url":"Gravitational_lens","recorded":1362891793,"links":109,"instances":["optics","optics"],"pdf":["http://www.mpa-garching.mpg.de/Lenses/WLRevEls.pdf","http://www.mpa-garching.mpg.de/Lenses/WLRevEls.pdf","http://www.ams.org/notices/200806/tx080600666p.pdf","http://www.ams.org/notices/200806/tx080600666p.pdf"],"categories":["Astrophysics","Effects of gravitation","Gravitational lensing|"],"headings":["Description","History","Explanation in terms of space–time curvature","Search for gravitational lenses","Measuring the weak lensing","Historical papers and references","References","External links","Featured in science-fiction works"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/A_Horseshoe_Einstein_Ring_from_Hubble.JPG/220px-A_Horseshoe_Einstein_Ring_from_Hubble.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Spacetime_curvature.png/250px-Spacetime_curvature.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Gravitational_lens-full.jpg/225px-Gravitational_lens-full.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip